{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7421d9b2-0ae9-4671-8fdd-aa8519eee727","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 changed **overload resolution** for `.Contains()` on arrays. The compiler now prefers:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)\n```\n\nover the LINQ version:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)\n```\n\nThis is because the implicit conversion `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>` (introduced in C# 12/13) is ranked as a *better conversion* than `T[]` → `IEnumerable<T>`. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be represented in expression trees — so you get a compile-time or runtime failure depending on how the tree is constructed.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nForce the compiler to pick the LINQ overload by casting to `IEnumerable<T>`:\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Collections.Generic;\n\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nOr call `Enumerable.Contains` as a static method directly:\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nEither approach pins the resolution to the `IEnumerable<T>`-based overload, which expression trees can represent.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8bec62ea-3cdf-4475-b953-c3186025c1b2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 related to LINQ expression trees and the `.Contains()` method on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to how extension methods are resolved. C# 14 introduces **extension members** (a new feature), but more relevantly, there's a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nThe key issue: In earlier versions of C#, when you called `array.Contains(num)` where `array` is `int[]`, the compiler would resolve this to `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<int>(I