ompiler's preference for the `MemoryExtensions` overload breaks the code. I can fix this by explicitly casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the LINQ version, or by calling `Enumerable.Contains` directly as a static method. Let me verify if this is actually a documented breaking change in .NET 10. I should also consider: maybe the issue is that in .NET 10, the C# compiler actually produces the expression tree successfully but targeting a `MemoryExtensions.Contains` method, and the expression tree interpreter fails at runtime because it can't handle `ReadOnlySpan<T>`.\n\nActually, expression trees in C# have a restriction: you can't use ref structs in them. So the compiler should give a compile-time error if it tries to resolve to a method that takes `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. \n\nBut wait - the C# spec says that overload resolution in expression tree contexts might have special rules. Perhaps in C# 14, the compiler correctly resolves to the `MemoryExtensions` overload but then fails because it can't express it in the expression tree.\n\nThe core issue is the overload resolution change favoring span-based `Contains` over LINQ's `Contains`, and expression trees can't handle ref structs. When the compiler tries to resolve `.Contains()` on an array within an expression tree, if it picks the `MemoryExtensions` overload that takes `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, it would hit a compile-time error since you can't represent ref struct types in expression trees. I've identified the root cause: C# 14 changed overload resolution to prefer the `MemoryExtensions.Contains` overload that takes a `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which is a ref struct that expression trees can't handle. The fix is straightforward—cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the LINQ version instead.","outputTokens":3056,"requestId":"D825:3A7531:5E756CE:6742861:69F155F2"},"id":"72fc10b6-3979-4a41-a64d-a6a057cf2ae7","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:51:58.330Z","parentId":"6ac134c8-e867-4fed-b563-38d2899cd64e"}
